&lt;/section&gt;&lt;h2 id="licence-assignments-transfers"&gt;Licence assignments (transfers)&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A company that is party to a licence may wish to sell an interest to another. Such a transfer is referred to here as a licence assignment.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Licence assignments are prohibited, except with the consent of the Secretary of State. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will consider any assignment made without prior consent as a very serious breach and grounds for immediate revocation of the licence under the terms of the model clauses attached to every licence.&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This restriction also applies to assignments between sister companies within a single company group, and to the withdrawal of a company from a licence that entails the assignment of rights to the remaining companies.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There is a type of allowed transaction in which two or more companies already on a licence adjust the proportions of their shares of the licence interests/liabilities – as long as no party enters or leaves the licence. These transactions can be made through the adjustment of a joint operating agreement (or similar agreement among the companies). They do not qualify as licence assignments. Visit the &lt;a rel="external" href="http://og.decc.gov.uk/en/olgs/cms/licences/licensing_guid/joint_operatin/joint_operatin.aspx"&gt;Operating agreements&lt;/a&gt; web page for more information.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="overview-of-procedures"&gt;Overview of procedures&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; operates a simple email-based application procedure for licence assignments. If we receive a complete form, there won’t be a need for further information (although we do reserve the right to contact the applicant if we deem it necessary).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This approach sees a marked reduction in regulation compared with earlier systems, under which applicants had to submit pre-execution drafts of all relevant legal documentation. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has also suspended the need to supply executed copies of all documentation after completion, but it does still require notification of completion and has added a facility to make this easy. Each consent carries a notification slip to be completed and returned by the assignee(s) as soon as possible post-completion.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We expect applications to have been agreed by all other necessary parties, at least in principle, before applications are submitted – particularly other parties to the licence. There is a box on the S8 form that requires confirmation of this.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will routinely seek advice about applications from the Licensing and Consents Unit’s asset teams, Exploration Team, Decommissioning Unit, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; financial advisers and others. We also circulate details of each application to Inland Revenue’s Oil Taxation Office (OTO).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="policy"&gt;Policy&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; generally considers increased volumes of licence assignments as a positive indication of companies improving their alignment on each licence. This does not mean they are regarded as mere tradable assets, and we expect companies to buy licence interests with a view to exploiting them – not merely to sell them on.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The following issues can cause concern about any particular assignment:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;technical and financial capacity of the licensee&lt;/strong&gt; – &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; must be satisfied the proposed new company is suitable for the licence, and that it has the capacity to participate fully in licence operations and discharge its licence obligations. See &lt;a rel="external" href="http://og.decc.gov.uk/en/olgs/cms/licences/licensing_guid/suitability_of/suitability_of.aspx"&gt;Suitability of licensees&lt;/a&gt; for more information.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;decommissioning costs&lt;/strong&gt; – financial capacity will be a greater concern if significant decommissioning costs are likely to be incurred by licensees. The dedicated decommissioning unit in Aberdeen is looking to ensure future decommissioning liabilities are covered.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;new entrants to the UK&lt;/strong&gt; – &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will always consider a company’s track record. If the company is new to the UK, we will try to take into account its overseas record. Where the proposed licensee is a subsidiary of a foreign parent, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will generally require an undertaking from the parent to support the licensee in its licence operations. See &lt;a rel="external" href="http://og.decc.gov.uk/en/olgs/cms/licences/licensing_guid/suitability_of/suitability_of.aspx"&gt;Suitability of licensees&lt;/a&gt; for more information.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;effect on operatorship arrangements&lt;/strong&gt; – &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will not approve an assignment if it would leave the licence without an approved operator. When an operator seeks to leave a licence, they will need to ensure the remaining partners have agreed a replacement operator and that &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; is ready to approve their choice. This is especially important for production operatorship. Approving an operator can take time, especially a production operator without a record of operating on the &lt;abbr title="United Kingdom Continental Shelf"&gt;UKCS&lt;/abbr&gt;.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;licence alignment&lt;/strong&gt; – this is not usually a concern for &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; but we might need to look carefully at a case in which one company gains a completely dominant position on a licence, or where one company has such a small interest that it is not motivated to participate fully in exploiting the licence but yet can still block it. This is more likely to be a concern where a field or a prospect near to development is affected.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;Intragroup assignments&lt;/strong&gt; – &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has no objection in principle to assignments to a sister company but if they are made specifically to dispse of the licence interests via a corporate sale, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will generally want to know who the buyer is before it is approved. Where the reason for the assignment is tax-related, we recommend first discussing it with the Oil Taxation Office.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;fragmentation of licence interests&lt;/strong&gt; – in some circumstances the creation of very small licence interests may be of questionable advantage to the &lt;abbr title="United Kingdom Continental Shelf"&gt;UKCS&lt;/abbr&gt;. It may, for instance, prejudice the licence group’s attempts to agree on new work by introducing new voices. However, such drawbacks may be outweighed by a new licensee’s expertise or experience. As a general rule, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; suggests any licensee seeking to create small licence interests (under 5%) should justify the transaction in the ‘extra information’ section of the application form.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;infrastructure&lt;/strong&gt; – this is a conceivable rather than routine issue, but &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; might be concerned if, for instance, it seemed an infrastructure owner was seeking to enter a licence group to influence tariffing negotiations.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;strong&gt;OPOL&lt;/strong&gt; – &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; expects all operators to be members of the Offshore Pollution Liability Association and to register each off its separate operatorships. Prospective new operators, to be approved as part of a licence assignment, can satisfy &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; that they are members by including their OPOL numbers at the appropriate place on the form.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="procedure-for-application"&gt;Procedure for application&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The current holder of the licence must gain permission to transfer it and therefore must lodge the application to &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;, even though in many cases much of the information &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; needs will have to come from the acquiring company. The application form below asks for all of the information &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will require for most cases. Use of the form is not obligatory, but it is recommended. Consent will not be granted unless &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has all of the required information.  &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;You can apply for consent to any number of assignments on the same form.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The form must be fully completed and in accordance with the guidance note. Avoid excessive precision when specifying the size of a licence interest; &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; generally does not record such figures beyond two decimal places.&lt;/p&gt;

