&lt;h2 id="licence-extensions"&gt;Licence extensions&lt;/h2&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As the oldest offshore licences expired in September 2010, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has incorporated a licence extension process to prevent the 100 producing fields they covered from having to close down. The policy for licence extensions applies only to Seaward Production Licences. Landward Production Licences are far more diverse and the case for extending them will continue to be considered on a case-by-case basis.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has already amended 1st and 2nd Round Licences1 and has communicated the policy on the extension of 3rd to 7th Round (inclusive) Licences.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="policy-1"&gt;Policy&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Production licences grant exclusive rights over a particular piece of acreage for a specified period. At the end of that period the acreage is returned to &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s competitive licensing system so the Secretary of State can decide who, if anybody, should have the next opportunity to exploit it. There are only a few circumstances where exceptions to this would be justified, of which well-managed producing fields are the most important.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 id="producing-fields"&gt;Producing fields&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Many North Sea fields are capable of much longer productive lifetimes than was foreseen in 1964, when the first Seaward Production Licences were designated 46-year lifespans. The Government issues production licences to accommodate production from oil and gas fields and if a field is well-managed and still producing when a licence expires, it makes sense to take steps to let the field carry on producing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Cessation of production on a field is not necessarily the end of its life. In some cases the field will have been exploited by old and inefficient infrastructure, leaving many hydrocarbons in the ground – and even if the current licensee has no interest in redeveloping the field with new techniques and equipment, somebody else might. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will not deem fields as being of no further interest once they cease production, but will instead release them for relicensing.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="duration-of-extensions"&gt;Duration of extensions&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A licence extension is justified only by continuing production, so it should continue for as long as production lasts and no longer. However, future field life cannot be predicted with confidence at the time of extension, so we cannot specify the duration of an extension as part of the extension process. It is also not acceptable to &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; that the licensee decides how long to keep a licence, and licensees would doubtless object to an approach that allows &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; to terminate licences when it sees fit. This leaves only one possible approach: an agreed formula, written into the licence at the time of extension, that determines its duration.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are various possibilities but none are without drawbacks:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;decommissioning is often associated with the end of field life and could act as a trigger in some cases. There is no necessary connection however, so in some cases it would give unacceptable results, e.g. if a field acts as a transportation hub or is used for CCS after its own production stops, decommissioning might not happen for decades after the end of the field’s own productive life. Besides, the use of decommissioning to trigger licence expiry would disincentivise timely decommissioning, and that would run counter to one of &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s most important objectives.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the ‘cessation of production’ (c.o.p.) procedure is a customary step at the end of a field’s life but it has no legal force and it is instigated entirely at the licensee’s discretion. If &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; were to rely on it to trigger the termination of a licence, the licensee would be able to retain a licence indefinitely by refraining from starting a c.o.p. discussion with &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;, regardless of whether or not production has actually ceased.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;zero production is associated with the end of field life, but it can happen at other times too, e.g. a field’s production can be temporarily ‘backed out’ of a pipeline, and major redevelopment work may also require a suspension of production. In both examples production would temporarily drop to zero, but the field’s life would not necessarily have to end. It may be reasonable to allow a licence to continue in such circumstances.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s approach is to define the end of field life as a set period with no production, but not enforcing licence termination at that end point. Instead, from that moment onwards unless and until production restarts, the Secretary of State is empowered to terminate2 the producing area. It is a matter at the Secretary of State’s discretion and &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will consider requests to let the licence continue on the grounds production will recommence within a reasonable period.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; acknowledges this solution is not perfect but is confident it will continue to work satisfactorily in practice.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For 1st-Round licences, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; originally agreed a two-year period with no production as the cut off for termination, but now considers this too long. In a case where a field has genuinely stopped production, the Secretary of State should not have to wait up to two years to terminate the field; and in cases of temporary suspension a shortened period is immaterial.For 2nd-Round and those thereafter, a one-year period of no production is considered the cut-off for termination. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h4 id="poorly-stewarded-fields"&gt;Poorly-stewarded fields&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; requires the highest standards of operator competence and environmental protection, and will take action immediately if an operator falls short. There are also minimum standards for stewardship of the UK’s oil and gas fields, in terms of their exploitation, because &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s policy is to maximise economic production. There is an expectation licensees will use their exclusive rights to a standard consistent with that policy. Most UK fields are already well-stewarded but &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; operates a Stewardship Programme to ensure there are no exceptions.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;We will press an existing licensee to improve their stewardship of fields not being operated to &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s satisfaction. If the standard continues to drop the Secretary of State reserves the right to refuse an extension to the licence at the end of its lifespan and instead invite competitive bids for a new licence over the field. The existing licensee would not be barred from entering the competition, and their knowledge, experience and track record would all be taken into account.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="prospective-areas-and-short-term-extensions"&gt;Prospective areas and short-term extensions&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There may be cases where a discovery is so close to becoming a producing field when the licence expires that &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will already have issued a production consent over it. In such a case it would generally be reasonable for &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; to grant a short extension to allow the discovery to start production. If the discovery did turn into a producing field during that extension, from then on it would be treated the same way as any other producing field.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In 2009 industry argued that some discoveries (and even prospects) had not even reached the production consent stage but were nevertheless being actively (if belatedly) brought to development. It argued these licences should be considered for extensions to allow production. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; agreed to consider such cases, but only where there was already an ongoing work programme.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There may be cases where factors beyond the licensee’s control keep them from starting a development until near the end of the licence term. Such factors might include late technical advances and availability of infrastructure. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; is prepared to consider short-term extensions in such cases but there is no presumption they will be agreed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Short-term extension are typically for two to three years. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will generally terminate the acreage if it has not reached production in that time. Where the discovery is brought into production however, the licence will automatically be extended long enough to cover production – on the same terms as any other producing field.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Short-term extension may or may not also carry intermediate breakpoints. Their purpose is to ensure a licensee cannot sit around for the whole extension period without making progress towards production. Each such breakpoint specifies a minimum amount of progress that must have been made by that time, e.g. a well to be drilled within one year. Failing that, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; can terminate the acreage. This specified amount of progress is called a ‘related work element’. It functions as a deadline – not as a commitment by the licensee to do the work.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will usually grant a short-term extension where it has recently issued a production consent, but in any other circumstances a licensee who wants a short-term extension must make a strong case for it and should not assume &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will agree.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="trading-moratorium-and-active-partners-on-prospective-areas"&gt;Trading moratorium and active partners on prospective areas&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Short-term extensions can only be justified to allow a little more time to a licensee who is working to achieve production as early as possible – not to allow more time for licence trading. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; feels strongly that where short-term extensions are approved, it is necessary to implement a trading moratorium on the prospective areas to ensure the extra time is devoted to work and not trading.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are two parts to this moratorium:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will not consent to licence assignments over prospective areas&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the Open Permission (Operating Agreements) will be amended to withdraw the Secretary of State’s pre-approval of any internal reassignment of licence rights that affects a prospective area.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;The moratorium applies for the period of the short-term extension – from the licence’s original expiry date (17 September 2010 for 1st-Round Licences) until the area ceases to be a prospective area by first production or termination.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The moratorium does not apply to inter-affiliate transfers.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="active-partners"&gt;Active partners&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;An ‘Active Partners’ procedure for 2nd-Round Licences applies in the period after a prospective area has been agreed by &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; but before the trading moratorim begins. This means that when a licensee asks &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; to consider a short-term extension over a prospective area, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; requires one or more of the current partners to declare themselves as the Active Partner – the person who will the see the discover through to first production. This prevents licensees being able to sell up and get out before the moratorium begins.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will not agree to a short-term extension if an Active Partner hasn’t been named&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;once a short-term extension has begun, trading by an Active Partner beyond that previously agreed by &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; as its trading strategy will cancel the short-term extension.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Active Partner mechanism applies from the moment a prospective area is created until the short-term extension begins. Beyond that the trading moratorium will be in effect so no trading will be allowed, by Active Partners or anyone else.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;
&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will not prevent trading during this period but will ensure a short-term extension does not begin if an Active Partner has either sold up or reduced their interest to a nominal level.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;
&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; accepts some limited trading during this period may not be unreasonable, where an Active Partner seeks to attract partners to their project, so any licensee that nominates themselves as an Active Partner but  intends to do any trading before the moratorium should ask &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; to agree their trading strategy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will not accept the nomination by one company of another as an Active Partner; each Active Partner must nominate themself.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;section class="attachment embedded" id="attachment_25026"&gt;&lt;div class="attachment-thumb"&gt;
    &lt;a href="https://assets.digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/15120/2rnd-lics.pdf" aria-describedby="attachment-25026-accessibility-help" class="thumbnail"&gt;
      &lt;img alt="" src="https://assets.digital.cabinet-office.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/15120/thumbnail_2rnd-lics.pdf.png"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;  &lt;/div&gt;
