&lt;/section&gt;&lt;h3 id="other-licensed-acreage"&gt;Other licensed acreage&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There is no case for an extension over acreage that is not in production – or well on the way to it – after 46 years under licence. The normal expiry process must be allowed to take its course over such acreage so it can be returned to &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s competitive licensing system, where it will rest with the Secretary of State to decide who, if anybody, should have the next opportunity to exploit it.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="multiblock-licences-1"&gt;Multiblock licences&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;It has become routine for parties to a production licence to arrange and rearrange their commercial interests within the licensed area. This rearrangement often entails defining subareas within the licensed area, e.g. two companies might split their equity interest 50/50 in a subarea that corresponds to a producing field, while one of them takes 100% interest in a complementary subarea that corresponds to the remaining exploration acreage. The division into subareas has created two issues for licensees:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;joint-and-several nature of licence liabilities and obligations links companies on one subarea to the liabilities arising on another&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;excessive fragmentation of a licensed area creates intercompany bureaucracy that puts a drag on further transactions. This is obviously a particular problem for the oldest licences, which have had the longest to accumulate this kind of fragmentation.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;Industry (via &lt;abbr title="Oil &amp;amp; Gas UK"&gt;OGUK&lt;/abbr&gt;) asked &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; to consider ways to split licences among these subareas. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has no objection in principle and devised a method to split the licences, but there are two major constraints on any such split:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;it must be compliant with all legislative provisions, including the Hydrocarbons Licensing Directive&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;it must create no risk that any liabilities or obligations will revert to the taxpayer&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s approach is to let the old licence expire gracefully and replace it with two or more replacement licences, each covering a single producing or prospective area. It was not practical to attempt this for 1st-Round licences but we will try to achieve it for 2nd-Round licences.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The advantage of doing it this way is that it saves companies a lot of time and effort if extension and splitting – each of which requires a major licence-amendment exercise – can be done together.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Replacement licences will not be offered to anybody who wasn’t a party to the old licence and they won’t cover acreage not covered by the old licence. This process amounts only to the rearrangement of an existing licence into a more efficient form composed of several documents. It should not be seen as the award of a new licence.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In some cases it may not be possible to achieve one area per licence. If two areas are too close together to draw a line between them, or if they exist at different depths and overlap, both will have to go on the same licence.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are some important points to note about this process:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;while &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; is willing to consider requests to split licences, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; is in no way committed to agree to any particular split.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the process of splitting a licence is too cumbersome and time-consuming to ever be seen as routine, and &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; reserves the right to choose which cases should be accorded the highest priority.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;where a multiblock licence has been split into two or more licences, liabilities incurred before that moment will continue, inherited by licensees on all the replacement licences – but there will be no joint-and-several liability between those licences for future liabilities yet to arise.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="mechanism"&gt;Mechanism&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;An extension amounts to an amendment of the licence, so it must be implemented by deed. All parties to the licence must sign the deed, which must finally be sealed3 and signed on behalf of the Secretary of State. There is a standard form of deed &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; uses in all cases (but obviously case-specific information such as area definitions will vary from one case to another).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The standard deed for 2nd-Round Licences is different to that used for 1st-Round Licences – to accommodate the additional task of splitting licences – but the terms governing producing and prospective areas are essentially the same.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will draft each deed and make it available to the companies for signature. Once it is signed by all parties, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will execute it on behalf of the Secretary of State and return the main copy to the licence administrator. A duplicate copy will be retained by &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;. Creating and circulating certified copies of the deed is a matter for licensees to consider.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="timing"&gt; Timing&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;A licence must be extended (i.e. the deed must be executed by all parties) before it expires. The licence’s original expiry date is therefore the final deadline for completion of an extension process. If the deed has not been executed in time, the licence will expire and any producing fields must be shut down until a new licence has been issued (and the Hydrocarbons Licensing Directive requires a full competition before any such licence would be issued).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Oil &amp;amp; Gas UK"&gt;OGUK&lt;/abbr&gt; has expressed its concern that some parties might seek to extract commercial advantage from their partners by threatening not to sign a deed. To prevent this from happening, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has agreed to seek execution of each Deed of Variation at least nine months before a licence’s expiry date, allowing time for &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; to deal with a potential situation by offering a replacement licence after a competitive process if absolutely necessary.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="details-of-the-deed"&gt;Details of the deed&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;at the moment of execution, the deed defines the producing and prospective areas.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;between execution of the deed and the original licence expiry date, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will enable the extension by written notice to the licensee. In most cases, &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will issue the notice with the executed deed.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;1st-Round licences – at the licence’s original expiry date, all parts of the licensed area other than producing and prospective areas are removed from the licence. The remaining areas continue.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;2nd-Round and remaining licences – the licence expires on schedule and is replaced by one or more replacement licences, each covering one producing or prospective area. The remaining acreage becomes available for relicensing.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;thereafter, each producing area continues while production lasts, and each prospective area continues for the duration of its own short-term extension and converts itself into a producing area if it reaches first production during that time. The Secretary of State is empowered to terminate a prospective area if it has not been brought to production by the end of its short-term extension,or if there is an intermediate deadline and the related work element is not completed by then. The Secretary of State is also empowered to terminate a producing area after any two-year period of zero production.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;once all of a licence’s producing and prospective areas have been terminated, the licence itself terminates.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="d-provisions"&gt;3D provisions&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; (and its predecessors) have always operated a 2D licensing system, in which each licence explicitly specifies a licensed area at the surface and implicitly also covers a volume of rock below that area down to the centre of the Earth.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Some have suggested that &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; should switch to 3D licensing, in which licences cover volumes of rock rather than areas of seabed, and different licensed volumes can overlap. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has not ruled out the idea of switching to 3D licensing – in which licences cover volumes of rock that than areas of seabed, and different licensed volumes can overlap – but it is currently not under consideration. It would raise particular issues, particularly regarding access to deep rocks for one licensee via shallow rocks licensed to somebody else.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Many of the claimed advantages of 3D licensing are already available to licensees, e.g licensees routinely divide their commercial interests within a licence group using 3D as well as 2D definitions, agreeing the terms of the division between themselves and specifying the terms of their cooperation in pragmatic case-by-case terms not available to &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; when defining the basic terms of its licences.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Nevertheless, and given the extensions process will eventually require the amendment of all licences anyway, it has eemed sensible to make such minor changes now as might be necessary to enable 3D licensing in the future. If &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; were to switch, there would only be a need to clarify the Secretary of State’s powers relating to field developments.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="future-cases"&gt;Future cases&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;After 2nd-Round Licences, the next licence expiries are not set to happen until 2014. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; reserves the right to review any policy at any time, but since 1990 all cases for extensions over well-stewarded producing fields have been formally accepted. This policy is not currently under review.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Given the element of uncertainty in on-field process and application procedure timings, it is never too early to approach &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; about an extension. Phone Jen Brzozowska on 0300 068 6030 for more information.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; recognises that a licensee may start work on a licence fully intending to achieve first production in time, but then find externally-imposed delays prevent them from doing so. This might constitute reasonable grounds for a short-term extension, but &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will not consider the case unless it is clear a short-term extension is actually needed – and not just as a routine precaution. The formal process for the extension would then only begin in the last year before licence expiry. We also recognise there are circumstances under which a licensee will want to be ensured of their chances of being granted a short-term extension at a later date. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will consider these cases but is not obliged to grant the licence extension. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Applicants should set out a clear and reasonable timetable of work, with well-defined milestones, that would facilitate a first production before the licence expiry date. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; may be able to provide a certain level of comfort about a short extension in the event of an unavoidable delay, but this will be conditional on the licensee maintaining at least a specified adherence to the timetable. The possibility of this assurance is not to be treated as an alternative to licensees making the best possible progress with their licence, or a means to keeping acreage out of &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s competition procedures.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has clarified this policy to licensees holding licences issued in the 3rd to 7th Round (verbally, at the fallow reviews held September 2011). Where it is clear that assets are not being worked in a timely manner, or are unlikely to attain FDP approval no later than six months before licence expiry, relinquishment will be requested.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Contact Jen Brzozowska on 0300 068 6030 for more information.&lt;/p&gt;

