&lt;/section&gt;&lt;h3 id="residence-requirements"&gt;Residence requirements&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There are different levels of residence requirement in accordance with what a company proposes to do in the UK.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To be a licensee, the company must have a place of business within the UK. This means it has one of the following:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;a staffed presence in the UK&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;a UK company registered at Companies House&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;registration of a UK branch of a foreign company at Companies House&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;This requirement exists for any company applying for a new licence and/or seeking to join an existing licence by assignment. It applies to all licences and all companies, regardless of whether they will or will not be the operator. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;To be a party to a licence that covers a producing field, a company must either:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;be registered at Companies House as a UK company&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;carry on its business through a fixed place of business in the UK (this normally requires a staffed presence)&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;This requirement is for tax purposes. Refer to section 148 of the Finance Act 2003 [External link] or article 5 of the OECD Guidelines for Multinational Enterprises [External link] for the definition of a ‘fixed place of business’.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There may be additional practical requirement to be an operator. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; will generally consider proximity and ease of communications as factors in an operator’s ability to manage operations properly, e.g. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; may consider that a particular field in the Southern North Sea might be operated as satisfactorily from either side of the North Sea but not from the other end either of Britain or Europe. Such issues will be considered on a case-by-case basis. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;h3 id="technical-expertises"&gt;Technical expertises&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt;’s main concern in this area relates to the operator. Non-operators don’t need to demonstrate as high a level of technical expertise, but we do expect the operating committee to be able to exercise responsible oversight. This means we wouldn’t allow a significant vote to be exercised by a company without the technical expertise.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;a rel="external" href="http://og.decc.gov.uk/en/olgs/cms/explorationpro/operatorship/operatorship.aspx"&gt;operatorship&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;h3 id="partnerships"&gt;Partnerships&lt;/h3&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Various types of partnership have been common in the UK for many years. &lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; has no objection in principle to the appearance of partnerships on Petroleum Act Licences but before allowing a partnership of any sort to join a licence would want to be assured that:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;decommissioning costs would remain satisfactorily covered by the decommissioning provisions of part IV of the Petroleum Act 1998&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the Secretary of State would have control over the withdrawal of the general partner and/or from the UK within a 1907 partnership&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;abbr title="Department of Energy and Climate Change"&gt;DECC&lt;/abbr&gt; would also want to be assured about the following concerns: &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;1907 partnerships are not subject to the same controls as companies because they are less secure in the assets they purportedly hold&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;the Secretary of State’s powers of revocation do not readily apply to a partnership where the idea of a change of control is less defined&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;The Department would discuss with HMRC the tax position of any partnership. Visit the &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/"&gt;HMRC website&lt;/a&gt; for further information.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Limited Liability Partnerships (LLPs) were introduced by the &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2000/12/contents"&gt;Limited Liability Partnership Act&lt;/a&gt; in 2000.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;contact Keith Mayo at &lt;a href="mailto:keith.mayo@decc.gsi.gov.uk"&gt;keith.mayo@decc.gsi.gov.uk&lt;/a&gt; to discuss them in the context of decommissioning provision, or &lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;Mike Hawkins at &lt;a href="mailto:mike.hawkins@decc.gsi.gov.uk"&gt;mike.hawkins@decc.gsi.gov.uk&lt;/a&gt; for information about them in the context of adherence to a licence contact. &lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;p&gt;The HMRC website also offers &lt;a rel="external" href="http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/oto/new_entrants.htm"&gt;guidance for new entrants to the North Sea&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;All other queries about the suitability of licensees should be addressed to:&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;div class="address"&gt;&lt;div class="adr org fn"&gt;&lt;p&gt;

